  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT225-kilavi">varaiviṭai vaittup pirivāṟkut tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Uttered by the confidante to him who separates after the
          time of marriage had been fixed.</p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT225">
          <l>kaṉṟutaṉ payamulai mānta muṉṟiṟ</l>
          <l>ṟiṉaipiṭi yuṇṇum peruṅkaṉ ṉāṭa</l>
          <l>keṭṭiṭat tuvanta vutavi kaṭṭil</l>
          <l>vīṟupeṟṟu maṟanta maṉṉaṉ pōla</l>
          <l>naṉṟimaṟan tamaiyā yāyiṉ meṉcīrk</l>
          <l>kalimayiṟ kalāvat taṉṉaviva</l>
          <l>ḷolimeṉ kūnta luriyavā niṉakkē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>O man from a land of big stones, where an elephant cow, while a calf</l>
          <l rend="indent2">feeds from her yielding <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">paya
            mulai</term> : this can be understood as <term xml:lang="ta">paya </term> (verbal root
            DEDR 3937) <term xml:lang="ta">mulai</term> "yielding breast", that is, a breast which gives milk.
            T.V.G. suggests <term xml:lang="ta">payam</term> "milk", which would have to be
            explained as a borrowing from Skt. payas.</note> breast, eats of the millet in the
            front-yard,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">if you do not totally forget <note place="foot">Here <term xml:lang="ta">
            amai-tal</term> is best explained as an auxiliary verb expressing final settlement.</note>
            [her] kindness,</l>
          <l rend="indent5">like a king who, having obtained distinction on the throne,</l>
          <l rend="indent5">forgets the aid which delighted [him] when he was lost,</l>
          <l rend="indent">− her lush, soft tresses, like the soft, excellent feathers</l>
          <l>of the bustling peacock, are worthy of you.</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
